Inland m1A1 Paratrooper Carbine, .30 Carbine, New Mfg.

This is the new Inland Manufacturing M1A1 Paratrooper Carbine.   I purchased it new a few months ago and never fired it.  After purchasing it, I saw something I liked better, now I want to sell it.

Caliber: .30 carbine
Magazine capacity: 15

The M1A1 carbines feature many of the same characteristics of the original Inland Carbines and are manufactured in the USA!

The M1A1 carbine is modeled after a late production 1944 M1A1 Paratrooper model with a folding "low wood" walnut stock, type two barrel band, and includes the same adjustable sights which were actually introduced in 1944.

The M1A1 includes a 15-round magazine and offers the same common features of the 1945 M1 model. Attention to detail has been carefully taken to produce a replica as close as possible to the original Inland production including cartouche marks and stampings in the wood specific features of the Inland Carbines.

In 1941, with the US being pulled into one of the greatest conflicts in world history, a division of General Motors was tasked to support the war effort.

The result was firearm history with Inland Manufacturing becoming one of the largest gun manufacturers in the US, producing nearly 3 million firearms in less than 5 years.

The most notable of Inland's firearm production was the .30 Caliber M1 carbine and the folding stock variant, the M1A1 Paratrooper model.

Dayton, Ohio was home for the original Inland company, and is now the home of the new Inland Manufacturing located just two miles from the original facility. Today's Inland Manufacturing is now producing a new line of .30 caliber M1 carbines and 1911 style pistols.

title: For Sale:  Savage Enfield No4 Mk1* US PROPERTY marked
postcontent:
I have a nice original No4 Mk1* Savage Enfield. It is US PROPERTY marked as it was used in the lend/lease program with the British during WWII. It is not date stamped as many of these Savage Enfield's are, based off its serial I believe its a late 1943 or early 1944 .

The rifle is numbers matching (even the 10 round magazine!)  besides the stock forend. I believe it was replaced at arsenal refinish before being dunked in cosmoline. It is savage stamped along with all the little parts on the rifle. The bore and muzzle are in good shape. 

When I received the rife it was absolutely saturated in cosmoline (storage grease). I removed the cosmoline from the rifle and treated the stock in gunstock oil and the metal in Barricade oil to preserve it, that's it. I've never fired it, never found the time to do so. 

Great rifle for the money and cool to own such a piece of history. I am selling because I have too many C&R rifles to be able to enjoy them all, it's time to thin the collection...  I have a 20 round box of .303 British that I will throw in. 

I will ship the rifle to a C&R holder for $35. Local pickup you will provide a copy of your drivers license for my records. Cash or USPS money order only.

Open to reasonable offers (these go for near $500 on Gunbroker, I don't like the hassle of GB). No trades.
